xplained etymology) became <i>Searo-</i> in Old English as the result of folk etymological association the Old English word <i>searu</i> ‘trick’; to this an explanatory <i>burh</i> ‘fortress, manor, town’ was added. The city is recorded in the Domesday Book as <i>Sarisberie</i>; the change of <i>-r-</i> to <i>-l-</i> is the result of later dissimilation."],"variants":[{"name":"Saulsbury","meanings":["English: variant of   Salisbury  ."]},{"name":"Saulsberry","meanings":["Altered form of English   Salisbury  ."]},{"name":"Salsbery","meanings":["English: variant of   Salisbury  ."]},{"name":"Salsbury","meanings":["English (Worcestershire): variant of   Salisbury  .","Jewish (American): adoption of the English surname (see 1 above) in place of   Salomon   or some other Jewish name beginning with <i>Sa-</i>."]},{"name":"Salsberry","meanings":["English: variant of   Salisbury  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mary of Salisbury was born in 1305, in Salisbury, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Richard de Cumbe II in 1325, in Brabourne, Kent, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1350, in Brabourne, Kent, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1305–1350":"1305–1350","1305–1360":"1305–1360","1333–1360":"1333–1360","1333–1395":"1333–1395","1305":"1305","1325":"1325","1333":"1333","1395":"1395","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","Salisbury, Wiltshire, England":"Salisbury, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Brabourne, Kent, England":"Brabourne, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1305–1350":"1305–1350","1305–1360":"1305–1360","1333–1360":"1333–1360","1333–1395":"1333–1395","1305":"1305","1325":"1325","1333":"1333","1395":"1395","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","Salisbury, Wiltshire, England":"Salisbury, Wiltshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Brabourne, Kent, England":"Brabourne, Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1305–1350":"1305–1350","1305–1360":"1305–1360","1333–1360":"1333–1360","1333–1395":"1333–1395","1305":"1